 "components": {
  "instruction": "You are assigned the task of categorizing digital banking or fintech customer support queries into one of 24 predefined categories. Each incoming task input consists of a single user message provided as a 'text' value, describing an issue, request, or complaint relevant to digital banking or fintech services. Your responsibility is to read the user's message carefully and select exactly one category from the fixed taxonomy below that best matches the specific situation or request:\n\nautomatic_top_up\nbalance_not_updated_after_bank_transfer\nbeneficiary_not_allowed\ncancel_transfer\ncard_payment_fee_charged\ncard_payment_not_recognised\ndeclined_cash_withdrawal\nexchange_rate\nexchange_via_app\nfailed_transfer\nget_disposable_virtual_card\nget_physical_card\npasscode_forgotten\npending_top_up\npending_transfer\nreceiving_money\nreverted_card_payment?\ntop_up_by_cash_or_cheque\ntop_up_reverted\ntopping_up_by_card\ntransfer_fee_charged\ntransfer_into_account\ntransfer_timing\nverify_my_identity\nverify_source_of_funds\n\nInstructions and domain-specific guidelines:\n\n- Each input will be a dictionary with a single string field titled \"text\", containing a customer’s message. Do not expect any other fields.\n- First, carefully read the entire customer message and identify the main problem, request, or inquiry.\n- Choose only ONE category that most specifically and accurately reflects the central issue described. Do NOT suggest or invent new categories, nor combine categories.\n- If a message describes receiving funds (such as a salary, payment, or transfer coming into the customer's account), use \"receiving_money\". Do NOT use \"verify_source_of_funds\" just because a user is asking about receipt or crediting of incoming funds.\n- Use \"verify_source_of_funds\" only when the message directly mentions bank or regulatory requests for information confirming the origin/source of received funds beyond normal transaction processing.\n- Use \"verify_my_identity\" only if the user is asked or needs to confirm their ID, regardless of transaction type.\n- If a customer queries about a top-up (adding funds to their account) being cancelled, reversed, or not completed, use \"top_up_reverted\". Do not confuse with \"cancel_transfer\", which is for cancelling outgoing monetary transfers between accounts.\n- For outgoing transfers, select:\n    - \"pending_transfer\" for transfers still processing with unresolved final status.\n    - \"failed_transfer\" if the transfer was not successfully completed for general reasons.\n    - \"beneficiary_not_allowed\" for transfers restricted due to recipient-specific rules.\n    - \"cancel_transfer\" only when cancellation of a transfer is explicitly requested or described.\n- For top-ups, use:\n    - \"pending_top_up\" if the top-up is still being processed or pending.\n    - \"topping_up_by_card\" if the issue is with topping up using a card.\n    - \"top_up_by_cash_or_cheque\" for issues related to cash or cheque top-up methods.\n- For card payment issues:\n    - Use \"card_payment_fee_charged\" if the user is questioning or disputing a fee on a card payment.\n    - Use \"card_payment_not_recognised\" for users not recognizing a transaction.\n    - Use \"reverted_card_payment?\" if the card payment was cancelled, refunded, or reversed (even without explicit user initiation).\n- For messages about receiving or exchanging money, know:\n    - \"exchange_rate\" is about currency conversion rates.\n    - \"exchange_via_app\" is for using the application to exchange currencies.\n- For any ambiguity, always select the most specific category possible—the one that most closely matches the details of the user's message.\n- Never make assumptions or go beyond what is directly stated in the customer message. If user intent is unclear, default to the most directly indicated issue.\n- Output your answer strictly in the following format:\nresponse\n<category_name>\n\nWhere <category_name> is the single best-matching category based on the provided taxonomy.\n\nExample:\nIf the input message is: \"Will you accept my salary if it's in another currency?\"  \nYour answer should be: \nresponse\nreceiving_money"
 },
